\maketitle

\begin{frame}{Problem}
A circle passes through the points \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix} and \begin{bmatrix}
4\\
5
\end{bmatrix}. If its centre lies on the line \begin{bmatrix}
-1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}x + 3 = 0, find its radius.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Solution}
The centre of the circle will lie on the line  \begin{bmatrix}
-1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}x + 3 = 0 and the perpendicular bisector of the line joining the points \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix} and \begin{bmatrix}
4\\
5
\end{bmatrix}. Basically it is the point of intersection of these two lines.


Consider the following points A = \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix} and B =\begin{bmatrix}
4\\
5
\end{bmatrix}
The mid point of the 2 points is       ( \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}
4\\
5
\end{bmatrix} ) / 2 = \begin{bmatrix}
3\\
4
\end{bmatrix}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{continued...}

A line passing through the point P = \begin{bmatrix}
3\\
4
\end{bmatrix} and perpendicular to the line joining the given points is \begin{equation}
    n^T(x - P) = 0
    \end{equation}
Where  n is B - A. x also satisfies the condition \begin{bmatrix}
-1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}x + 3 = 0.

therefore, n=\begin{bmatrix}
4\\
5
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
2
\end{bmatrix}
therefore, \begin{bmatrix}
2&2\\
-1&4
\end{bmatrix}x=\begin{bmatrix}
14\\
-3
\end{bmatrix}
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
That is solving for the intersection of the two lines , as the perpendicular bisector passes through the centre
\begin{equation}
x=\begin{bmatrix}
2&2\\
-1&4
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix}
14\\
-3
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\therefore  Centre: x=\begin{bmatrix}
6.2\\
0.8
\end{bmatrix}

\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
Radius is the distance between the centre and point on circumference


radius= distance between A and x,


x-A = \begin{bmatrix}
6.2\\
0.8
\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
4.2\\-2.2
\end{bmatrix} 
\therefore  Radius = \sqrt{(4.2)^2+(-2.2)^2} = 4.7413
\end{frame}

